  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use topology only when you can specify a collection of \u0026ldquo;open sets\u0026rdquo; with closure properties.\n¶Definitions A topology on a set XX is a collection T\\mathcal{T} of subsets of XX such that:\n∅\\emptyset and XX are in T\\mathcal{T}. Any union of sets in T\\mathcal{T} is in T\\mathcal{T}. Any finite intersection of sets in T\\mathcal{T} is in T\\mathcal{T}. The pair (X,T)(X,\\mathcal{T}) is a topological space.\n¶Vocabulary (plain language) Open set: a subset declared open by the topology rules. Union: combine sets by taking anything in any of them. Intersection: combine sets by taking only what is in all of them. ¶Symbols used XX: the underlying set. T\\mathcal{T}: the collection of open sets. ¶Intuition Topology is about which subsets count as \u0026ldquo;open\u0026rdquo; so that we can talk about continuity and gluing without relying on distance.\n",
  "name": "Topological Spaces",
